1 NAME Jacob T /Aaron/
1 SEX M
1 BIRT
2 DATE Dec 25 1832
2 PLAC Armstrong County
1 DEAT
2 DATE Jul 17 1902
1 NOTE Death of JACOB AARON  Jacob Aaron, whose serious illness was reported in the las
2 CONC t issue of the REPUBLICAN, died at his home in South Brookville on. Thursday  mo
2 CONC rning, July 17th, 1902, aged 69 years, 6 months and 22 days. Mr. Aaron had been 
2 CONC ailing for several years, and for several  months past. he had  been in a most c
2 CONC ritical condition, it being thought  by  the  members  of the family at various 
2 CONC times that his death was near at hand, but he would rally from his severe sick s
2 CONC pells and be quite well for a few days. Lately, however, he continued to grow wo
2 CONC rse and was unconscious for almost a day previous to his death.  Jacob Aaron was
2 CONC  born in Clarion county on the 25th day of December, 1832, and on the  6th of Se
2 CONC ptember, 1857, he was united in marriage with Miss Emily Cummins, who survives a
2 CONC nd who was a true and faithful  helpmeet  to him  during  all of  the eventful y
2 CONC ears of their  marriage up to | the time of his death. They resided | near Crate
2 CONC s  in Clarion county, until 1886, when they  moved  to Brookville.  They resided
2 CONC  here. until 1896, Mr. Aaron  working at his trade as a carpenter, but as he was
2 CONC  growing old and feeble and able to do but little work they moved during that ye
2 CONC ar to Pittsburg. City life, however, was not, congenial to them, and in 1898 the
2 CONC y moved back to  Brookville and again took possession  of their pleasant home on
2 CONC  the south  side of town  The deceased  was a devout member of the Roman Catholi
2 CONC c church, and he lead a life that caused him to he regarded by all who knew him 
2 CONC as an upright and honorable man. He was held in high esteem  by his circle of re
2 CONC latives and friends, with whom he left an ineffaceable  record for his many acts
2 CONC  of kindness it was his pleasure to perform. In addition  to his  aged wife he i
2 CONC s survived by six children, three daughters and three sons, as follows : Augusti
2 CONC ne, residing  at McKee’s Rocks, Pa.; Joseph, of Warren Edgar, of  Emlenton; Mary
2 CONC  Margaret, a Sister of Mercy at St. Joseph`s  Convent; Erie, Pa; Mrs. Ed. Reinse
2 CONC l, of Crates, Pa., and Miss Jennie, at home. Funeral services were conducted at 
2 CONC the Roman Catholic church in this place on Sunday morning, by Rev. Father  Georg
2 CONC e Winkler, after which the remains were taken to the graveyard near the deceased
2 CONC ’s former home at Crates, Clarion county for burial
