1 NOTE ALLISON ANCESTRAL GRAVES OF CLARION COUNTY, PA<br><br>If you are looking to visi
2 CONC t the gravesites of your ancestors, there are three cemeteries in Clarion County
2 CONC  that are the final resting places for descendants of Robert Allison.  As you ma
2 CONC y know, Robert Allison was one of three brothers (Andrew, Robert and James) who 
2 CONC arrived in America in 1750.  This document will help you locate the cemeteries w
2 CONC here some of our family are buried.<br>Some of the information in this memo was 
2 CONC obtained from a website called FindAGrave.com.  It’s an informative site with ab
2 CONC ility to search by cemetery and by individual name.  In addition, it often has o
2 CONC ther family members listed, where they are buried, and brief narratives or obitu
2 CONC aries.  <br><br>Robert Allison, one of the three original brothers, who I will r
2 CONC efer to as the first generation, was married to Rebecca (Beckie Beard).  They ar
2 CONC e buried in Bethel Presbyterian Church Cemetery in Indiana, PA (Indiana County).
2 CONC   Robert Allison lived from 1730 (some data says 1727) to 1805 and Beckie Beard 
2 CONC from 1730 to 1807.  Robert and Beckie had seven children – John, Andrew, Tate, R
2 CONC obert James Thomas, Jane.<br>Bethel Cemetery is the oldest in Indiana County and
2 CONC  among the oldest in Western Pennsylvania. 223 graves sites have markers, but th
2 CONC ere are many unmarked graves. In 1935 a fire in the clerk of session's home dest
2 CONC royed the maps and cemetery records.  I haven’t visited this cemetery to know fo
2 CONC r certain whether Robert’s grave is marked, but no image is shown on FindAGrave.
2 CONC <br> <br> Tate (Tait) Allison who was part of the second generation, was married
2 CONC  to Mary (Pollie) Henry.  They are bd in Seceder Presbyterian Cemetery, which is
2 CONC  located in Clarion County.  Seceder Cemetery is very first burial ground in Cla
2 CONC rion County and is located north of Mechanicsville, PA on a dirt road just off R
2 CONC oute 66.  Tate Allison lived from 1759 to 1850 and Pollie from 1760 to 1830.  Ta
2 CONC te and Pollie had eleven children – Rebecca (Beckie), Sarah (Sallie), Robert, He
2 CONC nry, John, Jane (Jennie), Hannah, Nancy, Thomas, Mary Ann, Tate.  <br>There is a
2 CONC  map attached to this document to assist with locating the cemetery.  Once you’v
2 CONC e turned from Route 66 onto the narrow dirt road leading to the cemetery, drive 
2 CONC to the top of the hill.  Under a stand of trees, you’ll find this very old cemet
2 CONC ery.  Many of the grave markers are weather worn and difficult to read.  However
2 CONC , Tate Allison was a veteran of the American Revolutionary War, so his marker wa
2 CONC s replaced in recent years by the Daughters of the American Revolution organizat
2 CONC ion.  In order to find his grave, walk north toward I-80 from the narrow dirt ro
2 CONC ad.  His grave is under a very large oak tree in the cemetery and has a US Flag 
2 CONC adornment.  A word of caution…when you are leaving the cemetery, be very careful
2 CONC  when entering Route 66.  The field of vision is quite limited from both directi
2 CONC ons and cars sometimes speed through that area.<br><br>   <br> <br><br>Tate Alli
2 CONC son, of the third generation, was married to Mary Calhoun.  They are buried in L
2 CONC imestone Cemetery, which is located in Limestone, PA (Clarion County).  Tate All
2 CONC ison lived from 1801 (some data reads 1807) to ?? and Mary Calhoun lived from 18
2 CONC 05 to 1900.  Tate and Mary had nine children – Samuel, Mary, Sarah, Asenath, Flo
2 CONC rinda, James B, Charles, Elizabeth, Robert C.<br>I was unable to locate Tate and
2 CONC  Mary’s gravesites, but there does appear to be a family plot area in a corner o
2 CONC f the cemetery.  Perhaps that would be their final resting place.  According to 
2 CONC records, there are a number of Tate and Mary’s children also buried in the Limes
2 CONC tone Cemetery.  Records indicate that Sarah, Asenath, Florinda, James, and Charl
2 CONC es are interred there, but their graves don’t appear to be marked.<br>In additio
2 CONC n, there are other Allison relatives buried in Limestone cemetery.  Robert Allis
2 CONC on was a brother of the second-generation Tate, and he and his wife, Jane Englis
2 CONC h Allison, are located in Limestone Cemetery.  He lived from 1790 to 1877 and Ja
2 CONC ne lived from 1800 to 1888.  Robert’s grave marker is quite ornate and appears t
2 CONC o be made of metal rather than stone.  Two of their children, Rebecca and Sarah 
2 CONC Allison Cyphert are buried there, too, but their graves could not be located.<br
2 CONC ><br>   <br> <br>Robert C Allison, of the fourth generation, was married to Jane
2 CONC  Eliza Baird Allison. Robert lived from 1850 to 1929 and Jane Eliza lived from 1
2 CONC 856 to 1924.  Robert and Jane Eliza had ten children – Lester Clark, Eva, Mary, 
2 CONC Roy, William Earl, Elizabeth, Paul, John and Ethel.<br> are buried in Limestone 
