1 NOTE ANTHONY C. FASENMYER, now retired, has been a constructive factor inthecommerci 
2 CONC al affairs of Kansas City, Kansas, and many of the results ofhisthirty-one year 
2 CONC s of activity still stand and have enteredpermanentlyinto the life and well bei 
2 CONC ng of the community.<br><br>Mr.Fasenmyer was born at Fryburg in Clarion County, 
2 CONC Pennsylvania,January 10,1857. He was the third of five children whose parents we
2 CONC reJacob andFrances (Fletcher) Fasenmyer. His grandfather BalthaserFasenmyer l iv
2 CONC ednear Strassburg in Alsace, France. He spent seven yearsas a soldier undert he 
2 CONC great Napoleon. From there he emigrated to Americaand located atFryburg, Pen nsy
2 CONC lvania, having come from a town of asimilar name inBaden, Germany. He was a farm
2 CONC er. Jacob Fasenmyer was forfifty years amerchant in Pennsylvania. His child ren 
2 CONC attended the littleredschoolhouse in the country and that was the only adva ntag
2 CONC es theyhadoutside of a good home training.<br><br>After leaving school Anth onyC
2 CONC . Fasenmyer clerked in his father`s storeand thus acquired a fundamentalkn owled
2 CONC ge of merchandising. At the age ofseventeen his father startedhim in a sto re in
2 CONC  a small country town nearFryburg, and he wasidentified with that business until
2 CONC  he removed toKansas.<br><br>It wasdue to the persuasion of Father Kuhls, of St.
2 CONC  Mary`s Hospital inKansasCity, Kansas, and an old friend of the Fasenmye r famil
2 CONC y, thatAnthonyFasenmyer came out to the West and with his wife and one c hildset
2 CONC tled atWyandotte, now Kansas City, Kansas. His first business washandlin g reale
2 CONC state in partnership with Dan Rooney, and Dan Furlong. Thefirm was knownas Roone
2 CONC y, Furlong & Fasenmyer. With the collapse of theboom in Kansasthis fir m was one
2 CONC  of many that was caught in financialstraits, and Mr.Fasenmyer lost pr actically
2 CONC  all he had gained by hisprevious years ofeffort and the year followin g he spen
2 CONC t as manager ofthe Kansas Catholic,a local publication, and then with money borr
2 CONC owedfrom the A. M. NorthrupBanking Company he once more engaged in bu sinessfor 
2 CONC himself at 530Minnesota Avenue. That was his business home fortwenty years, and 
2 CONC in 1911he sold out and retired. His two brothers FrankP. and Joseph G.Fasenmyer,
2 CONC  also conducted a clothing store in the sameblock and on thesame s ide of the st
2 CONC reet. All these three brothers madecomfortablefortunes as business men of the ci
2 CONC ty.<br><br>Mr. Anthony Fasenmyer wasone of the organizers of the Commercial Bank
2 CONC and of the Kansas TrustCompany and Citizens Savings Bank, and wa s vicepresident
2 CONC  and a directorin each organization for fifteen years. He hasacq uired a large a
2 CONC mount ofreal estate, and owns the two story buildingat the corne r of Seventh an
2 CONC dMinnesota avenues which he built and whichbears his name.<br><b r>OnJanuary 13,
2 CONC  1885, Mr. Fasenmyer married Mrs. Mary (Sterner) Groner.Shewas born at Fryburg, 
2 CONC Pennsylvania. Nine children were born to them,two ofwhom died in infancy. Cornel
2 CONC ius is a business man in Kansas City,Kansas,and Eugene G. is also a young busine
2 CONC ss man, both the sons havingrisen tocommendable prominence i n local affairs. Lo
2 CONC uisa is the wife ofHarry Maukof Orlando, Florida, where he f ollowed contracting
2 CONC , and theyhave twochildren. Christinia lives at home. Mary i s a Sister of Chari
2 CONC tyat Butte,Montana. Julia and Frances are trained nurses at St. Joseph`sHospital
2 CONC  inKansas City, Missouri. Anthony is a student in the elect ricalengineeringand 
2 CONC mechanical department of Notre Dame University, inIndiana. Colletteis still at h
2 CONC ome. Mr. Fasenmyer has given his childrenliberal advantage sin the way of educat
2 CONC ion and all the comforts of a goodhome.<br><br>Mr.Fasenmy er has always exercise
2 CONC d his independent judgment in politics,hasstood for every thing that would make 
2 CONC a better and greater community,buthas never sought any of fice. He and his famil
2 CONC y are active members ofSt.Mary`s Catholic Church and Mrs. Fasenmyer is one of th
2 CONC e foremostchurchworkers and has done much to alleviate t he conditions of the po
2 CONC orandneedy in her home city.<br><br>Transcribed from vol ume 4, pages2065-2066 o
2 CONC f A Standard History ofKansas and Kansans, written and compiled by William E. Co
2 CONC nnelley,Secretary of the Kansas State HistoricalSociety , Topeka. Chicago: Lewis
