1 NOTE Anthony C. Fasenmyer<br>ANTHONY C. FASENMYER, now retired, has been aconstructi 
2 CONC ve factor in thecommercial affairs of Kansas City, Kansas, andmany of the resul 
2 CONC ts of histhirty-one years of activity still stand andhave entered permanentlyin 
2 CONC to the life and well being of thecommunity.<br><br>Mr. Fasenmyer was born at Fr 
2 CONC yburg in Clarion County,Pennsylvania,January 10, 1857. He was the third of five 
2 CONC children whoseparents wereJacob and Frances (Fletcher) Fasenmyer. His grandfat h
2 CONC erBalthaserFasenmyer lived near Strassburg in Alsace, France. He spentseven y ea
2 CONC rsas a soldier under the great Napoleon. From there heemigrated to Americaand lo
2 CONC cated at Fryburg, Pennsylvania, having comefrom a town of asimilar name in B ade
2 CONC n, Germany. He was a farmer. JacobFasenmyer was forfifty years a merchant in Pen
2 CONC nsylvania. His childrenattended the littlered schoolhouse in the country an d th
2 CONC at was the onlyadvantages they hadoutside of a good home training.<br><br>A fter
2 CONC  leavingschool Anthony C. Fasenmyer clerked in his father`s storeand thus acquir
2 CONC ed a fundamental knowledge of merchandising. At the age ofseventeenhis fat her s
2 CONC tarted him in a store in a small country town nearFryburg,and he was ident ified
2 CONC  with that business until he removedtoKansas.<br><br>It was due to the per suasi
2 CONC on of Father Kuhls, of St.Mary`s Hospital inKansas City, Kansas, and an ol d fri
2 CONC end of theFasenmyer family, thatAnthony Fasenmyer came out to the West and with 
2 CONC hiswife and one childsettled at Wyandotte, now Kansas City, Kansas. His first bu
2 CONC siness washandling real estate in partnership with Dan Rooney, andDan Fu rlong. 
2 CONC Thefirm was known as Rooney, Furlong & Fasenmyer. With thecollapse of th eboom i
2 CONC n Kansas this firm was one of many that was caughtin financialstraits, a nd Mr. 
2 CONC Fasenmyer lost practically all he hadgained by hisprevious years of effo rt and 
2 CONC the year following he spent asmanager ofthe Kansas Catholic, a local pub licatio
2 CONC n, and then with moneyborrowedfrom the A. M. Northrup Banking Company he once mo
2 CONC re engaged inbusinessfor himself at 530 Minnesota Avenue. That was his business 
2 CONC homefortwenty years, and in 1911 he sold out and retired. His two brot hersFrank
2 CONC P. and Joseph G. Fasenmyer, also conducted a clothing store in thesam eblock and
2 CONC  on the same side of the street. All these three brothersmadecomforta ble fortun
2 CONC es as business men of the city.<br><br>Mr. AnthonyFasenmyer was one o f the orga
2 CONC nizers of the Commercial Bankand of theKansas Trust Company and Citiz ens Saving
2 CONC s Bank, and was vicepresidentand a director in each organization for fifteen yea
2 CONC rs. He hasacquired alarge amount of real estate, and owns the two st ory buildin
2 CONC gat thecorner of Seventh and Minnesota avenues which he built and wh ichbearshis
2 CONC  name.<br><br>On January 13, 1885, Mr. Fasenmyer married Mrs. Mary (Sterner) Gro
2 CONC ner.She was born at Fryburg, Pennsylvania. Nine children wereborn t o them,two o
2 CONC f whom died in infancy. Cornelius is a business man inKansas City,K ansas, and E
2 CONC ugene G. is also a young business man, both thesons havingrisen to commendable p
2 CONC rominence in local affairs. Louisa isthe wife ofHarry Mauk of Orla ndo, Florida,
2 CONC  where he followedcontracting, and theyhave two children. Christin ia lives at h
2 CONC ome. Maryis a Sister of Charityat Butte, Montana. Julia and France s are trained
2 CONC nurses at St. Joseph`sHospital in Kansas City, Missouri. Anthony i s astudent in
2 CONC  the electricalengineering and mechanical department of NotreDame University, in
2 CONC Indiana. Collette is still at home. Mr. Fasenmyer hasgiven his c hildrenliberal 
2 CONC advantages in the way of education and all thecomforts of a good home.<br><br>Mr
2 CONC . Fasenmyer has always exercised hisindependent judgment in poli tics,has stood 
2 CONC for everything that wouldmake a better and greater community,but has never sough
2 CONC t any office. Heand his family are active members ofSt. Mary`s Catholic Church a
2 CONC nd Mrs.Fasenmyer is one of the foremostchurch workers and has done much toallevi
