2 CONC s <br>would support origin from within present day German borders. He immigrated
2 CONC  on 15 Sep 1749 to Philadelphia, PA.12,\3 And <br>ers or Andreas Grett immigrate
2 CONC d from Germany to Philadelphia, landing 15 Sept 1749. He was listed as Andreas, 
2 CONC Jun. to <br>distinguish him from his father Andreas, Sen. In addition a Johannes
2 CONC  Grett was listed, apparently his brother. Since the two <br>sons took the oath 
2 CONC of Allegience, it appears both were over 16 years, and in fact, Andreas was abou
2 CONC t 28 years. He was <br>imported on the ship Phoenix, John Mason master, from Rot
2 CONC terdam, but last from Cowes, England. Andreas Grett <br>(Gret/Greth/Crate) was b
2 CONC orn in southern Germany (?), and immigrated to America in 1749. He signed a will
2 CONC  in 1805 in <br>Winsor Twp., Berks Co., PA.14 He died on 5 Jan 1811 in Winsor Tw
2 CONC p., Berks Co., PA.IS Death location assumed, as this is <br>where he owned land.
2 CONC  <br>He had an estate probated on 16 Jan 1811 in Winsor Twp., Berks Co., pA.16 A
2 CONC bstract reads: Greth, Andrew, Winsor <br>[twp.). 1805 [written] - Jany 16, 1811 
2 CONC [proved]. To wife Magdalena all estate during life. Afterwards to son Andrew 1 <
2 CONC br>pound. Remainder to 3 sons, John, Michael and Nicholas and 2 daughters, Magda
2 CONC lena Bauman and Barbara Seibert <br>[Seiffert] in equal shares. Exc.: son Nichol
2 CONC as. Wits.: Daniel Rieser and Jacob Sterner. Translation. <br>He was buried in Th
2 CONC e Most Blessed Sacrament Roman Catholic Cemetery, Bally, P A. 17,\0 Andreas poss
2 CONC ibly was indentured <br>though this is not confirmed, as first American records 
2 CONC do not appear until in 1765 at Bally in the Catholic register. This is <br>about
2 CONC  15 years after immigration. He settled inwhat was then Winsor Township, Berks C
2 CONC o., PA, when on 18 June 1771 he <br>obtained ~ land warrants for 45 acres (one f
2 CONC or 25 and a second for 20 acres). The land was located in the southern part of <
2 CONC br>the then Winsor township, which today is actually in the southern part of Per
2 CONC ry Township. By 1780 he was assessed, in <br>Winsor Twp., with 235 acres, 3 hors
2 CONC es, 5 cattle and a tax of20.0.0. In 1781 the assessment read 205 acres, 3 horses
2 CONC , 4 <br>cattle and a tax of3.0.0. Sources indicate the family was Catholic, and 
2 CONC many ofthe original family are buried in the Greth <br>Private cemetery in Winso
2 CONC r (now Perry) Township, Berks Co., P A. The family name a) so appears as, Kret, 
2 CONC Crate or Create, <br>especially for those who moved west to Clarion Co. (town of
2 CONC  Crate) .. However for those branches of the family remaining in <br>Berks Co. t
2 CONC he name Grett or Gret became standard as Greth. <br>He was married to M. Magdale
2 CONC n UNKNOWN between 1750 and J 753. Estimated from single immigrant to birth of <b
2 CONC r>children. M. Magdalen UNKNOWN was born about 1720. She died on 4 Feb 1806 in W
2 CONC insor Twp., Berks Co., P A. Assu <br>med she was living on homestead. She was bu
2 CONC ried in The Most Blessed Sacrament Roman Catholic Cemetery, Bally, PA. \0 <br>An
2 CONC dreas GRETT and M. Magdalen UNKNOWN had the following children: <br>Andrew Gredt
2 CONC  and the Blessing from Pope Benedict XIV<br>The reign of PopeBenedi ct XIV was f
