2 CONC onsin - Madison<br>ILKINSBURG, PA. - Gregory Charles Reinsel d iedsuddenly on We
2 CONC dnesday, May5, 2004. He was born on March 10, 1948, inWilkins burg, Pa., son toP
2 CONC hilip and Ann Reinsel. He graduated fromCentral Catholic High School inPittsburg
2 CONC h, in 1966. He then received hisB.S. in mathematics in 1970, M.S. in 1972, and P
2 CONC h.D. in mathematics andstatistics in 1976, from theUniversit y of Pittsburgh. Gr
2 CONC eg and his wife,Sandy, married on May 15,1976; also that yea r he became an assi
2 CONC stantprofessor in the statisticsdepartment of the University of Wisconsin; anass
2 CONC ociate professor in1983; and a full professor in 1987. Greg served asan associat
2 CONC e chairmanof the statistics department from 1995 until 199 7,and chairman 1997un
2 CONC til 2001. In 1994, he was elected as an AmericanStatistic alAssociation fellow f
2 CONC or outstanding professional contributionsin thefield of s tatistical science, pa
2 CONC rticularly for research in timeseriesand longitudinal dat a analysis. In 2000, h
2 CONC e was also a fellow oftheInstitute of Mathematical Statis tics. He was a member 
2 CONC of theAmericanStatistical Association (ASA), Institute of MathematicalStatistics
2 CONC (IMS), Royal Statistical Society, International Statisti calInstitute,and the Am
2 CONC erican Geophysical Union (AGU). He authored andco-autho redthree books: `Time Se
2 CONC ries Analysis - Forecasting and Control`with GeorgeBox and G.M. Jenkins, `Multiv
2 CONC ariate Reduced - Rank Regression`with RajaVelu, and `E lements of Multivariate T
2 CONC ime Series Analysis.` Gregalso wasinvolved with the Ce nter for Integrating Stat
2 CONC istical andEnvironmentalScience at the University of C hicago. Greg had studied 
2 CONC thedepletion ofthe ozone layer for many years with a t eam of scientistsfrom NAS
2 CONC A,National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration and theNational Centerfor Atmo
2 CONC spheric Research. He loved classic movies andcontinu ed a lifelong interest in b
2 CONC uilding models of military aircraftand vehicles. Hea lso loved to jog and hike, 
2 CONC especially in our nationalparks. He enjoyedplaying b asketball for many years wi
2 CONC th MSCR andwatching golf andfootball as well. He is survived by his beloved wife
2 CONC  of28 years, Sandy;children, Christopher (Jennifer) of Neenah, and Sarah ofBould
2 CONC er, Colo.;brothers John Reinsel of Pittsburgh, Pa. , and Jim (Janet)Reinsel ofCo
2 CONC lumbia, Md.; and niece, Kara Reinsel of Boston, Ma ss.Funeral serviceswill be he
2 CONC ld on Monday, May 10, 2004, at 11 a.m. atDIVINE S AVIOR UNITEDMETHODIST CHURCH, 
