2 CONC br>Number of Household Members Over 25:	2<br>Number of Household Members:	4<br>H
2 CONC enry and his wife were born in what is now Germany. This is documented in the 18
2 CONC 80 census record of their son Anthony. It appears that they came with their pare
2 CONC nts<br>Henry appears in the 178os tax roll in pine township and then at the Bapt
2 CONC ism  for his son John H in Lebanon. It may be that a Missionary priest recorded 
2 CONC the record there.Henry and his family, minus Daniel who seems to have been old e
2 CONC nough to be on his own at that time, move to Derry Township,Westmoreland County 
2 CONC before 1805. John H. would have been about 7 or 8 years old at the time. It appe
2 CONC ars that John H. returned to Lebanon County and perhaps lived for awhile with Da
2 CONC niel to help him on the farm or perhaps he returned to help Daniel`s widow after
2 CONC  Daniel`s death.<br>     In what is the first generation in the colonies, we hav
2 CONC e Conrad Reinsel Henry's father, Henry Reinsel  who lived near Lebanon in the la
2 CONC te 1790`s (John and Anthony were baptized there) and moved to Derry Township, We
2 CONC stmoreland County before 1805. In that year hi s wife Elizabeth appears as a spo
2 CONC nsor for Elizabeth Arnst, 1 year old daughter of Jacob and Margaret Arnst, who w
2 CONC as baptized on November 23, 1805. Most likely this Jacob Arnst was really Jacob 
2 CONC Arents a child or grandchild of Jacob and Margaret Arents who were the grandpare
2 CONC nts of Margaret Arents the wife of John Reinsel. It ispossible that this Henry R
2 CONC einsel identified as John Reinsel`s baptismal record s as John Reinsel`s father 
2 CONC may have been named George Henry Reinsel.  A George He nny Reinzell and his wife
2 CONC  Elizabeth appear on page 60 of Baptisms of Western Pennsylvania as sponsors of 
2 CONC George Henry Bridge on November 1, 1810.<br>     On April 14 in 1807, Henry and 
2 CONC Elizabeth Reinsel bought 222 acres of land from William Montgomery in Derry Town
2 CONC ship, Westmoreland County for$750 (Vol 8, Page 31, Westmoreland Deeds).<br>     
2 CONC Census records show that this Henry Reintzel was born between 1750 and 1760. He 
2 CONC died in 1841 in Westmoreland County  He married Elizabeth who was born between 1
2 CONC 750 and 1760 and died in 1837.<br>Henry Reintzel Sr. and Henry Reintzel Jr. were
2 CONC  subscribers to the log church at Sportsman`s Hall in th e Latrobe area, in 1810
2 CONC . By 1820,Henry Reintzel Sr. appears to have been living with his son or daughte
2 CONC r and their family. Most likely Henry Jr. because they never appeared as separat
2 CONC e households in the census as long as Henry Sr. was living. <br>The 1830 Census,
2 CONC  page 169, roll 164, shows Henry Rancil as the head of the following household: 
2 CONC 1 male less than  5, 1 male 10 and less than15,1 male 4 0 and less than 50 -- mo
2 CONC st likely Henry Jr.,  1 male 70 and less than 80 -- most likely Henry Sr., 1 fem
2 CONC ale 20 and less than 30 --likely Henry Jr`s. second wife, Leddy., and 1 female 7
2 CONC 0 and less than 80--probably  Elizabeth, Henry Sr`s. wif e.<br>     The children
2 CONC  of Henry Sr.and Elizabeth include a daughter, Rachel, who was born in 1789, acc
2 CONC ording to the Burgoon Genealogy and died on May15, 1854. She married Adam Kuhn.R
2 CONC achel Reinzel Kuhn died at the age of 66. Rachel appears to have been a sister o
2 CONC f John, Daniel, Anthony,Conrad, Henry and George.<br><br><br><br>Tax List: 1754-
