1 NOTE In 1860 John Henry Reinsel Was living with the Daniel Aaron (b.1827)family.    O
2 CONC bituary from Clarion Democrat, January 30, 1919  Mr. John Henry Reinsel, for man
2 CONC y years a prominent and highly respected citizen of Limestone township, started 
2 CONC Thursday, Jan.28 [sic], 1919 on his journey to that bourne from which no travele
2 CONC r ever returns. Mr. Reinsel was a son of John and Margaret Reinsel and was born 
2 CONC Sept. 13, 1841, in Lebanon, Pa.  When a small boy he came to Clarion county with
2 CONC  his parents in an immigrant wagon.  He lived the greater part of his life in Li
2 CONC mestone township, during which he proved himself to be a splendid farmer. Some y
2 CONC ears ago he moved to Pittsburgh where he made his home until recently he resided
2 CONC  with his daughter in whose home he closed his eyes to all things earthly and we
2 CONC nt away in peace.  He was the last of a family of four boys and three girls.  In
2 CONC  the year 1865 he was united in marriage with Miss Jane Aaron, at St. Nicholas C
2 CONC hurch, Crates.  His wife preceded him in death but he is survived by the followi
2 CONC ng children: B.J. Reinsel, Limestone township; Sister Mary Joseph, of Titusville
2 CONC ; Mrs. James Murray, Hawthorn; Harry Reinsel, Redbank township; Clarence and Gen
2 CONC evieve Reinsel, Pittsburgh; Frank and Merle Reinsel, of the 97th Aero Squadron i
2 CONC n service in France.  The body was conveyed to St. Nicholas Catholic Church at C
2 CONC rates on Jan. 28th, where the funeral service, including a requiem high mass was
2 CONC  conducted by Rev. Fr. M. Fitzgerald, and the body laid to rest in the cemetery 
2 CONC adjoining.
