2 CONC tizens, closed his early career Tuesday, January 27, 1903, being about 73 years 
2 CONC of age. The obsequies will be held this Thursday morning at St. Nicholas Church 
2 CONC at Crates, with Rev. Father Dwyer officiating, when all that is mortal of our ne
2 CONC ighbor and friend will be laid to rest. Mr. Reinsel more than fifty years ago ca
2 CONC me from Lebanon county, Pa., to make his life`s home in this section and it is b
2 CONC elieved settled on the farm where he died. He was the first of his family to set
2 CONC tle here. Soon after coming here he was married to Miss Ann Aaron, a daughter of
2 CONC  the late Daniel Aaron. To them were born six children who survive, the mother h
2 CONC aving passed away a few years ago. The surviving children are: Guy N. Reinsel, C
2 CONC rates; D.A. Reinsel, Hawthorn; P.M. Reinsel at the old homestead near Shannondal
2 CONC e; Dr. H.T. Reinsel, Pittsburgh; Dr. L.M. Reinsel, Shannondale; and Mrs. Mary J.
2 CONC , wife of S.B. Conner of Limestone township. The deceased is also survived by tw
2 CONC o brothers and one sister namely: Jonathan A., Shannondale; John H. Reinsel, Cra
2 CONC tes; and Mrs. Rebecca McAnnich, Franklin, Pa. Mr. Reinsel was a man of the highe
2 CONC st honor and strictest integrity and he filled a place in the community in which
2 CONC  he commanded the esteem and confidence of all. He leaves behind him a precious 
2 CONC memory.
