1 NOTE Margaret "Peggy" Therese Allison (Reinsel)<br><br>March 11, 1930 - December 12, 
2 CONC 2018<br><br>Burial Date: December 17, 2018<br><br>Family and friends will be rec
2 CONC eived Sunday, December 16, 2018, from 4 p.m. to 8 p.m. A Mass of Christian Buria
2 CONC l will be celebrated on Monday, December 17, 2018, at 2 p.m. at the St. Nicholas
2 CONC  Church in Crates.<br><br>Obituary Viewed 85 times<br><br>    Obituary<br>    Co
2 CONC ndolence<br><br>Margaret “Peggy” Therese Allison (née Reinsel), age 88, passed f
2 CONC rom this earthly realm into glory to be with her Lord and Savior on Wednesday ni
2 CONC ght, December 12, 2018, surrounded by her family at home in Fairmount City, PA. 
2 CONC She was born March 11, 1930 to Robert “Bob” D. and Susanna (McGranahan) Reinsel 
2 CONC on a farm near Frogtown, PA. <br><br>Peggy’s life can be characterized by three 
2 CONC words: Faith, Family and Fellowship.<br><br>Peggy attended a one room schoolhous
2 CONC e from 1st thru 8th grade near her parents’ farm. She graduated from Clarion-Lim
2 CONC estone High School in 1948 and then attended New Kensington Business School. She
2 CONC  met the love of her life in high school as they sat next to one another in clas
2 CONC s. Peggy was an assertive young woman. In 10th grade, she asked Bob to a Sadie H
2 CONC awkins dance as their first date. She creatively made him a corsage of cabbage a
2 CONC nd radishes. In her senior year, Peggy was voted the Clarion-Limestone High Scho
2 CONC ol Prom Queen.<br><br>Peggy married her high school sweetheart Robert “Bob” C. A
2 CONC llison on Thanksgiving, November 22, 1951 at St. Nicholas Catholic Church in Cra
2 CONC tes, PA. She moved to Fort Leonard Wood, MO to be with Bob as he served his coun
2 CONC try in the Army. Afterward they moved to Washington County, PA then Butler, PA b
2 CONC efore returning to the Frogtown area to buy a farm next to Peggy’s parents in 19
2 CONC 56. In 1973, they bought Peggy’s parents farm moving into the house where she wa
2 CONC s born.<br><br>Peggy had a welcoming spirit, frequently thinking of others and t
2 CONC heir needs first. She loved to have family, friends and ‘friends of friends’ in 
2 CONC her home for an overnight stay, a meal around the kitchen table or a neighborly 
2 CONC visit. Her home was often the scene of holiday and family celebrations. Peggy or
2 CONC iginated the Allison family Autumn Leaf Festival “Soup Day” which celebrated its
2 CONC  44th annual event this year. Always curious about other cultures, she has welco
2 CONC med guests from Bulgaria, Chile, Germany, Greece, Israel, Japan, Kyrgyzstan, Pal
2 CONC estine and Uzbekistan. She was a master of stretching a prepared meal to accommo
2 CONC date unexpected visitors. Her candy bowl was known for always being generously f
2 CONC illed.  No one was a stranger in her home and no one could leave before signing 
2 CONC her guest book and getting a hug from Peggy. <br><br>Peggy served in many capaci
2 CONC ties with the Hawthorn Girl Scout Troop when her daughters were active in the gr
2 CONC oup. For years Peggy opened her home as a SAFE (Stop Abuse For Everyone, Inc.) e
2 CONC mergency shelter to women and children in need.<br><br>Peggy was a lifelong pari
2 CONC shioner at St. Nicholas Catholic Church. For decades she was involved teaching c
2 CONC atechism, helping with the church dinners, cleaning the church, crafting the alt
2 CONC ar cloths and serving in the Rosary Altar Society.<br><br>Peggy thrilled in seei
2 CONC ng God’s creation as she traveled to Alaska, Florida, Hawaii, Ireland, Southwest
2 CONC  United States and the Canadian Maritimes. She collected unique and exquisite st
2 CONC ones from locations that she visited. Peggy enjoyed reading, sewing and painting
2 CONC . Many of her art pieces are on display at her home and family homes. She loved 
2 CONC taking pictures. A camera was always nearby and she delighted in sharing the pho
2 CONC tos with everyone.<br><br>She is survived by her husband of 67 years, Bob; and n
2 CONC ine children, Stephen Allison and wife Diane Hartman of Fairmount City, PA; Ther
2 CONC esa Allison of Wexford, PA; Ruth Clover of Wilkinsburg, PA; David Allison and Da
2 CONC lena McCauley Rupp of South Bethlehem, PA; Linda Allison-Doane and husband Ron o
2 CONC f Horseheads, NY; Kenneth Allison and wife Dawna of Fairmount City, PA; Thomas A
2 CONC llison of Clearfield, PA; Susan Allison and husband Patrick Koeppl of Limestone,
2 CONC  PA; Tate Allison and wife Rebecca of Fisher, PA. She also leaves behind 20 gran
2 CONC dchildren, 20 great-grandchildren and a large extended family including numerous
2 CONC  nieces, nephews, and friends.<br><br>She is also survived by two brothers, Edwa
2 CONC rd Reinsel and wife Edie of Fairfax, VA and Robert Reinsel and wife Bernice of F
2 CONC airfax, VA; sister-in-law Yvonne Stewart of Xenia, OH and brother-in-law Edgar S
2 CONC hofestall of Corsica, PA.<br><br>Peggy was predeceased by her parents, infant so
2 CONC n John, her sister Mary Susanne Miller, brother-in-law Rudolph Miller, brother-i
2 CONC n-law Lee Allison, brother-in-law Robert Stewart and sister-in-law Patricia Shof
2 CONC estall.<br><br>The Allison family wishes to thank Diana and Janianne Patton for 
2 CONC their loving dedication in caring for Peggy over the past several years. A speci
2 CONC al thank you to the Clarion Forest VNA Hospice staff for their care of Peggy dur
2 CONC ing the past weeks and to everyone who helped care for Peggy.<br><br>Family, fri
2 CONC ends, and others, whose lives Peggy touched are invited to the Alcorn Funeral Ho
2 CONC me, 4065 Brookville Street, Hawthorn, PA, from 4-8 PM on Sunday, December 16, 20
2 CONC 18, to reminisce, grieve, support each other and, of course, just chat. A Mass o
2 CONC f Christian Burial will be celebrated on Monday December 17, 2018 at 2:00 PM at 
2 CONC St. Nicholas Catholic Church in Crates, PA with Father Samuel Bungo officiating.
2 CONC  <br><br>Memorial donations can be made in Peggy’s name to the Clarion Forest VN
2 CONC A Hospice Program, 271 Perkins Road, Clarion, PA 16214 and/or a charity of the d
2 CONC onor’s choice.
