2 CONC in 1758 and died in Butler County in 1840.He is listed on the Muster roll of Pen
2 CONC nsylvania, as a Volunteer in Berks County in June of 1780 to serve to July 15, 1
2 CONC 781 in Company 4, (page 184 Pennsylvania Archives Series 5, Vol. 5). Also, a Val
2 CONC entine Rentz ell,who I believe is the same person, is listed as a member of the 
2 CONC Lieutenant Colonel`s Company, Ninth Pennsylvania, Continental Line in 1783. Page
2 CONC  464 Pennsylvania Archives Series 5 Vol.3. A Valentine Reinsel (Reintzel), who w
2 CONC as in born 1758 and died 1840 was a veteran of seven months service of Washingto
2 CONC n's Revolutionary Army during which time he collected 17 pounds 10 shillings for
2 CONC  his service. He married Mary (Anna Marie) in the spring of 1782 in York County,
2 CONC  Pa .They had nine children with the following dates of birth. It seems that the
2 CONC y may have been married by a priest from Conewago.  It is possible that the miss
2 CONC ionary at Conewago traveled some distance.   Valentine Reintzel married Anna Mar
2 CONC ie(Mary) ___ in the spring of 1782.     Valentine and Anna Marie`s children s ee
2 CONC m to have been:   Henry, born Oct.1783     Elizabeth, born March 1786, Valentine
2 CONC , born August 1787,  Rosina, born  1789. Baptized by a Priest from Goshenhoppen.
2 CONC  (Rosina married George Ruffner),    Catherine, born 178 ?  Baptized by a Priest
2 CONC  from Goshenhoppen,  Mary, born May 1791, Eva, born Feb. 1794,   Nancy, born  Oc
2 CONC t. 1796,  Marlin or Marti n born Jan. 1, 1800,      Margaret, (Peggy) born  1802
2 CONC     <br> After a short stop in Huntington County, where they were counted int he
2 CONC  census of 1800, this family of Valentine moved to Butler County, in the Buffalo
2 CONC  Creek-Donegal area, before 1809.  In 1800, the Census in Huntington County show
2 CONC ed this family as including: one male 10 to 16, 1 male 16 to 26, 1 Male 45+, 4 f
2 CONC emales less than 10, 3 females 10-16, and 1 female26-45.<br><br>     Valentine a
2 CONC nd sons Henry and Valentine and daughter Elizabeth later lived at Buffalo Creek.
2 CONC  This is confirmed by the censuses of 1810,1820 and 1830 and later. The Goshenho
2 CONC ppen Register shows that Valentine Reintz (Reintzel) and Anna Marie Reintz (Rein
2 CONC tzel)had a daughter Rosina in August of 1787 and also a Felton Reinzel (whichis 
2 CONC obviously a misnomer for Valentine) and his wife Anna Marie Reinzel had a daught
2 CONC er Catherine Reinzel, born on the 13th of some month in 1789,baptized Nov 1, 178
2 CONC 9.<br><br> In the Catholic Baptisms of Western Pennsylvania, a Valentine Reinsel
2 CONC l  and his sister Elizabeth were sponsors of Mary Ann Maholland [Mulholand] on J
2 CONC une 5, 1808 (p 55). This brother and sister were quite clearly the children of t
2 CONC he The Valentine born in 1758. The Mulhollands lived in Donegal Township Butler 
2 CONC County.<br><br>     Valentine Reinsel,  and Rose Buck were sponsors of Valentine
2 CONC  Ruffner, son of George Ruffner and Rose [Ransel] Ruffner on July 15, 1819 (Bapt
2 CONC isms of Western Pennsylvania p 80). Rose Ransel Ruffner born in 1787 was most li
2 CONC kely the daughter of Valentine. She appears to have been the Rosina identified i
2 CONC n the Goshenhoppen Register s.<br><br>     According to information in A Proud P
2 CONC eople a Proud Herritage, Valentine Reinsel and his wife Catherine Ruffner, likel
2 CONC y a sister of George Ruffner, lived in the Vogelbacher Settlement near the home 
2 CONC of Casper Shaffer in 1830 through 1841. According to the 1840 Census they had 3 
2 CONC sons and one daughter. Seven people lived in their house. No information about w
2 CONC here this family went after 1840 has been found.
