1 NOTE John Robert Rensel<br>Erie Times-News (PA) - Tuesday, June 2, 2015<br>John Rober
2 CONC t Rensel, of Erie, died Saturday, May 30, 2015, at the age of 88, after a<br>sho
2 CONC rt illness. John was born October 28, 1926, he was the son of the late William<b
2 CONC r>Albert Rensel and Johanna Spanggaard. John attended Summit Central School and<
2 CONC br>graduated from Academy High School. John served his country during World War 
2 CONC II<br>in the Army Air Corps, and remained active and instrumental in Erie politi
2 CONC cs, church,<br>and community throughout his life. He was an avid baseball partic
2 CONC ipant and<br>enthusiast, and was a semi-pro pitcher for Crawford County's Canado
2 CONC hta Lake Team,<br>before settling down to start a family. As a lifelong resident
2 CONC  of Summit and Erie<br>County, John lived in Millcreek Township for over 50 year
2 CONC s. He was a founding and<br>lifelong member of Holy Trinity Council 4123 of the 
2 CONC Knights of Columbus, and a<br>founding member of the Perry Highway Hose Company.
2 CONC  He was an active member of<br>St. George Parish, and served as President of the
2 CONC  Men's Council, was a member of<br>their Ushers Club, founded the Youth Athletic
2 CONC  Association, and was the founder of<br>both the St. George's golf and bocce lea
2 CONC gues. He was a coach to many little leaguers,<br>including his sons in Belle Val
2 CONC ley and Millcreek Youth Associations. He was also a<br>member of the Maennerchor
2 CONC  Club and a Flaming Zukor. He was active in all aspects<br>of the Erie County po
2 CONC litical process, serving both as an elected official and by<br>accepting numerou
2 CONC s appointed positions. In his efforts to continually improve his<br>community, J
2 CONC ohn Rensel had served as Judge of Elections, Millcreek Township<br>Committeeman,
2 CONC  Millcreek Township Auditor (Secretary), Draft Board<br>Member/Appointee and Cam
2 CONC paign Manager for numerous local candidates. He<br>served as President of the Mi
2 CONC racle Mile Seniors Group and headed up the Millcreek<br>Senior Center Committee,
2 CONC  which organized the Township's first senior center. John<br>retired from Zurn I
2 CONC ndustries Hydromechanics Division, as their Manager of<br>Manufacturing in 1989,
2 CONC  and previously worked at Bucyrus Erie, as head of Payroll<br>and later in opera
2 CONC tions. He was preceded in death by three brothers, William A.<br>Rensel, James R
2 CONC ensel, and Harold A. Rensel. He was survived by his beloved wife<br>Evelyn, to w
2 CONC hom he was married for 67 years, and he was blessed with four sons and<br>one da
2 CONC ughter: sons, John William Rensel, of Punxsutawney, Pa. (Cheryl), Gerald<br>Robe
2 CONC rt Rensel, of Mt. Vernon, Ohio (Mary Jane), Jeffrey James Rensel of Erie<br>(Dar
2 CONC lene), a daughter, Kathleen Sue Johnson, of Ellicott City, Md. (Carroll), and Jo
2 CONC el<br>Edward Rensel of Medford Lakes, N.J., five beautiful grandchildren, Daniel
2 CONC  John<br>Rensel, of Erie, Ian Christopher Rensel, of North Olmsted, Ohio, Kristi
2 CONC  Leigh Rensel of<br>Cleveland Heights, Ohio, and Mary Elizabeth and Rory Sarah J
2 CONC ohanna Rensel of<br>Medford Lakes, N.J., and many nieces and nephews. Friends ar
2 CONC e invited to call on<br>Wednesday from 3 p.m. to 5 p.m., at Brugger Funeral Home
2 CONC s & Crematory, 1595<br>West 38th St., at Greengarden Boulevard, and to attend a 
2 CONC Funeral Mass at St. George
