1 NOTE Gordon J Rice, Jr., of Clarion, died peacefully at home early Wednesday morning,
2 CONC  June 13, 2018. Born September 30, 1931, in Findlay Township, Allegheny County, 
2 CONC PA, he was the son of Anna and Gordon J. Rice Sr.<br><br> <br><br>A resident of 
2 CONC Clarion since age 5, Gordon attended Immaculate Conception School through 12th g
2 CONC rade. Sure that he would join his father’s International Harvester Dealership, h
2 CONC e completed business courses at several universities including Penn State, Pitt,
2 CONC  and Clarion as well as an International Harvester Training College in Georgia. 
2 CONC  He took sole ownership of Rice Equipment in 1970 shortly after his father’s dea
2 CONC th.  Gordon sold the business in 1986 but rather than retire he decided to pursu
2 CONC e a new line of work.<br><br>He began selling obselete tractor parts under a new
2 CONC  business name, Antique International Tractor Parts, and it ran from 1987 until 
2 CONC 2011. The day before his 80th birthday, Gordon passed the business on to his nep
2 CONC hew and son. For the last 7 years he kept busy selling collectibles on ebay. Gor
2 CONC don’s hobbies included playing cards, racquetball, and traveling, especially by 
2 CONC train.<br><br> Gordon’s life in Clarion County included years of active communit
2 CONC y involvement. His legacy starts with 21 years as a member of the Lions Club, as
2 CONC  well as membership in the Jaycees for 16 years. Gordon also served as Autumn Le
2 CONC af Festival Parade Marshall for 20 years beginning in 1958. He was a member of t
2 CONC he Pennsylvania State Farm and Power Equipment Association board for 16 years. G
2 CONC ordon joined the Catholic Knights of St. George in the 1950s, and eventually thi
2 CONC s group was converted into the William Penn Association for which he was vice-pr
2 CONC esident for Clarion Branch 114.  He joined the Clarion Knights of Columbus when 
2 CONC Immaculate Conception Church received a charter and remained an active knight fo
2 CONC r 60 years reaching the 4th degree.  He was a member of the Clarion IC Cemetery 
2 CONC board of directors for 49 years and served as board president for 21 years.<br><
2 CONC br>Gordon also served on the board on the Clarion Chamber of Commerce and Busine
2 CONC ss for 7 years and acted as president from 1976-77.<br><br>He is survived by his
2 CONC  wife of 67 years, Dorothy Reinsel Rice, as well as his 3 daughters: Sherrie (Br
2 CONC ad) Smith of Franklin, WI, Mary Jean (Nick) Bagileo of Laurel, MD and Kathleen (
2 CONC Rob) McElravy of Shippenville as well as 13 grandchildren. They include Gregory,
2 CONC  Ian, Meghan, Jacob, Keyne, Natalie and Emily Rice; Maggie Swingle; Anthony, Bri
2 CONC dget, and Maximilian Bagileo; and Clayton and Milton McElravy. He was also bless
2 CONC ed with 6 great-grandchildren. Also surviving is his brother Rev. William Rice o
2 CONC f Fryburg, PA and sisters Jeanne (Fran)  Paff of Newburgh, NY and  Arlene Speerb
2 CONC recher of Sagamore Hills, OH.  He is also survived by two daughters-in-law, Jane
2 CONC t Rice, of Lakeville, PA, and Bonnie Rice, of Clarion.<br><br>Gordon was precede
2 CONC d in death by his daughter Karen, and sons Joseph and William.
