1 NOTE Obituary<br>Evelyn Frances Rensel (Slodownik), age 91, of Erie passed away peace
2 CONC fully surrounded by her<br>family on Saturday, April 3, 2021. She was born at ho
2 CONC me on June 30, 1929, the daughter of the late<br>John and Mary Slodownik.<br>The
2 CONC  youngest of four siblings, Evelyn grew up surrounded by her loving and protecti
2 CONC ve brothers,<br>her parents, and farm animals in Summit township. She knew first
2 CONC hand that ‘running around like<br>a chicken with your head cut off’ was not just
2 CONC  a phrase! Having lived her entire childhood and<br>teenage years without indoor
2 CONC  plumbing, she attended Hamilton one room schoolhouse and then<br>Academy High S
2 CONC chool where she graduated with the Class of 1947. She enjoyed Saturday matinee<b
2 CONC r>movies and square-dancing. She met and married her loving husband, John R. Ren
2 CONC sel, and they<br>were married Jan 31, 1948, until his passing in May 2015. They 
2 CONC shared 67 years of mostly loving<br>bliss. She worked briefly for General Electr
2 CONC ic as a comptometer operator and later as a work-athome marketing surveyor. She 
2 CONC found her true joy by caring and raising her five wonderful<br>children: John, G
2 CONC erry, Jeff, Kathy, and Joel. Family remained her life-long first priority, lovin
2 CONC g<br>nothing more than to be surrounded by her children, listening and laughing 
2 CONC loudly with them for<br>hours on end. She was a member of St. Matthew’s in the W
2 CONC oods’s Church where she and John<br>were married. In 1957, she became a lifelong
2 CONC  parishioner of St. George Church in Millcreek and<br>was a founding and long-ti
2 CONC me member of their Women’s Golf and Bocce Leagues. She also was a<br>member of t
2 CONC he Knights of St. John‘s mixed doubles bowling league. She enjoyed traveling wit
2 CONC h<br>her husband and long-time traveling companions Joyce and Jim DaValle where 
2 CONC they visited<br>Hawaii, Florida, the Carolinas, Arizona, and many other wonderfu
2 CONC l sites in America. Evelyn was a<br>voracious reader of novels (mostly romance a
2 CONC nd mystery), People magazine, and doing daily<br>crossword puzzles. She loved he
2 CONC r morning tea, cooking, cleaning, and caring for her family. She<br>was a wonder
2 CONC ful baker of cakes and cookies, notably her cookies and fudge at Christmas and h
2 CONC er<br>secret nut bread recipe which she made for Easter. Now only Evelyn and the
2 CONC  angels above know
