1 NOTE In Leutershausen, Germany in 1748, ChristianTopper/Tapper/Dapper/Dabberand his f
2 CONC amily boarded the ship `Judith` forthe New World. In many waysChristian could be
2 CONC  described as the`Stammvater des Amerikaner Stamms` --the Father of the Ameri ca
2 CONC n Family.He was the progenitor of the Topperline in the United States. Initia ll
2 CONC y,from Northampton County and then toAdams, Somerset, and WestmorelandCounti es 
2 CONC in Pennsylvania, and Frederickand Carroll Counties in Maryland,Hampshire Cou nty
2 CONC , in Virginia or WestVirginia, thence to Ohio, Indiana,to Illinois, to Michi gan
2 CONC , Texas,Oklahoma and onto California, WashingtonState and elsewhere. The Top per
2 CONC line is a microcosm of migration acrossthe breadth of this country._________ ___
2 CONC ___ From the ship`s papers readsas follows: `And at the sametime and place, the 
2 CONC foreigners whose nameswere also underwritten beinglately imported in the sh ip, 
2 CONC Judith, CaptainJames Tait, Commander, fromRotterdam but last from Cowes did also
2 CONC  takethe foregoing oath to thegovernment. [Qualified Sept. 15, 1748.] Approximat
2 CONC ely forty men were onthe ships list: Christian as `Christian (+)Dapper.` The + i
2 CONC ndicates thathe made his mark because he could not write.This probably e xplains
2 CONC  whyhe never corrected the spelling of his name.The journey to Pennsylva niafell
2 CONC  naturally into three parts. The firstpart, and by no means theeasiest , was the
2 CONC  journey down the Rhine toRotterdam or some other port.Gottlieb Mittelb erger in
2 CONC  his work, `Journeyto Pennsylvania in the year1750` describes: This jou rney las
2 CONC ts from thebeginning of May to the endof October, fully half a year, am id suchh
2 CONC ardships as no one is able todescribe adequately with their misery. Thecause is 
2 CONC because the Rhineboats from Heilbron to Holland have to pass by26 cus tom houses
2 CONC , at allof which the ships are examined, which is donewhen it suits t heconvenie
2 CONC nce of the customs house officials. In themeantime the ship withall t he people 
2 CONC are detained long, so that thepassengers have to spendmuch money. The trip down 
2 CONC the Rhine lasts four,five even six weeks.Because things are very dea r there, be
2 CONC ople havenearly all they haveduring that time. The second stage of t he journey 
2 CONC isfrom Rotterdam toone of the English ports. Most of the ships calle d atCowes o
2 CONC n the Isleof Wight. Christian probably travelled from Philadelphiat o Goshenhopp
2 CONC en,PA which in near Bally, PA where he probably hadfriends.________ ____________
2 CONC __ `Sometime in 1780 Christian and hisfamily movedto the Conewago a rea of York 
2 CONC County, where he died on July13, 1789. Hewas interred at the Conewg ao Catholic 
2 CONC Chapel Churchyard. Histombstonewas one of those early black slate s tones, with 
2 CONC Germaninscription, whichis weathered and difficult to read. The ins criptionread
2 CONC s as follows:-IHS HIER RUHER den leib Cristian Dabber Gehohden 11 December 1715G
2 CONC eftor:den 13 july 1789 Alt 73 jahr, 7 Monath 2 Tag.` --SteveGiland EARLY FAMILIE
2 CONC S OF FREDERICK COUNTY MARYLAND AND SOUTHCENTRALPENNSYLVANIA p. 125 <br><br>Sourc
2 CONC e in part for informationconcerning Christian`s voyage on the ship ,Judith: Jose
2 CONC ph R. Topper, WFTVol 65, Tree 2395.<br>
